
When a process is put in the background with &, the shell sets its
disposition for SIGINT to SIG_IGN (ignore).  This is POSIX-specified
behavior for job control shells.

The key consequence: you cannot trap SIGINT in a backgrounded
script.  Even if the script has trap '...' INT, the SIG_IGN
disposition inherited from the parent takes precedence — the trap
is never installed because the signal was already set to ignore
before the script started.
